  What happens internally

  Condition B: working memory only
  In B, the agent gets:

  - recent conversation history from Redis
  - resolved structured context from recent turns
  - no episodic retrieval
  - no semantic hints

  Internally:

  - the system looks back over the last N turns, where N = window_size
  - it includes those turns in the prompt as recent history
  - it also tries to resolve referenced context keys like region, customer, period, etc. from those recent turns

  So:

  - wm2 = only the last 2 turns are available
  - wm5 = last 5 turns
  - wm10 = last 10 turns

  Condition C: working + episodic
  In C, the agent gets:

  - everything from B
  - plus retrieved prior turns from Chroma episodic memory

  Internally:

  - it first uses working memory exactly like B
  - if needed, it retrieves the top k prior episodes from the same session
  - those retrieved episodes are appended into the prompt as “relevant prior retrieved episodes”

  So:

  - ep1 = add 1 retrieved prior episode
  - ep10 = add 10 retrieved prior episodes

  Condition D: full stack
  In D, the agent gets:

  - working memory
  - episodic memory
  - semantic memory

  Internally:

  - same as C
  - plus semantic notes retrieved from the source-specific semantic store
  - those notes are schema/glossary hints, for example source-specific definitions or mapping hints

  So:

  - sem1 = add 1 semantic hint
  - sem4 = add 4 semantic hints

  Why increasing these numbers can hurt

  More memory helps only if the extra memory is:

  - relevant
  - precise
  - not distracting

  Otherwise it creates prompt noise.

  Here is how that happens.

  1. More working memory can dilute the important context
  If you include too many previous turns:

  - old turns may conflict with the current question
  - irrelevant earlier filters or entities stay visible
  - the model may anchor on stale context

  Example:

  - turn 2: “North America”
  - turn 6: “Now only Europe”
  - if too much history is present, the model may mix both and generate the wrong filter

  So wm10 can be worse than wm2 if the most relevant context is actually very recent.

  2. More episodic retrieval can bring in near-matches instead of exact matches
  Retrieval is similarity-based, not perfect logic.
  If you retrieve too many episodes:

  - some are relevant
  - some are only loosely similar
  - the model sees many possible prior contexts and may pick the wrong one

  Example:

  - current question asks about one company and one quarter
  - retrieved episodes include several similar company/quarter discussions
  - the model uses the wrong one

  That is why ep10 can hurt compared with ep1.

  3. More semantic hints can overconstrain or distract
  Semantic memory is helpful when it gives a precise disambiguation.
  But too many hints can:

  - introduce unrelated schema guidance
  - make the prompt longer and noisier
  - bias the model toward the wrong interpretation

  Example:

  - one good hint says “use customer_id, not company_name”
  - three extra hints talk about different schema patterns
  - the model may overfit to the wrong hint cluster

  That is why sem4 can be worse than sem1.

  4. Bigger prompts are not automatically better prompts
  Even if the model can handle long context, longer context still means:

  - more competing signals
  - more token budget spent on memory instead of the actual question
  - more chances for the model to attend to the wrong detail

  So more context is not the same as better context.

