• Short answer: helpful, but not strong enough by itself for EB-1A.

  In USCIS terms:

  - 3 published papers can support the “authorship of scholarly articles” criterion.
  - 1 patent can help support “original contributions of major significance”, but USCIS explicitly says a patent or publication alone does not prove major
    significance. They want evidence of impact: citations, commercialization, adoption, expert letters, etc.
  - Even if you meet 3 criteria, USCIS still does a final merits determination and asks whether your whole record shows sustained acclaim and that you are among the
    small percentage at the top of the field.

  Official USCIS sources:

  - EB-1 overview (https://www.uscis.gov/working-in-the-united-states/permanent-workers/employment-based-immigration-first-preference-eb-1)
  - USCIS Policy Manual, Extraordinary Ability (https://www.uscis.gov/policy-manual/volume-6-part-f-chapter-2)

  What that means practically:

  - 3 papers: good, especially if they are real scholarly papers and later cited.
  - 1 patent: good supporting evidence, especially if allowed/granted and tied to real product impact.
  - Together: solid foundation, but still usually not enough unless combined with things like:
      - critical role evidence
      - judging/reviewer roles
      - product/public impact
      - citations/adoption
      - third-party recognition

  For your profile, a stronger combination would be:

  - 3 papers
  - 1 patent
  - documented critical role at your company
  - at least a few judging/reviewer activities
  - public/product impact evidence
  - some independent letters and recognition

  So my honest view is:

  - one patent + three papers is good
  - one patent + three papers + your leadership/impact evidence could become strong
  - one patent + three papers alone is usually not where I would want to file

  This is not legal advice; an EB-1A attorney should assess the full record. But from an evidence-building standpoint, you should treat the patent and papers as core
  technical pillars, not the whole case.

