  - Memory is the story for multi-turn tasks.
  - Stateless collapses on Tier 2 and Tier 3.

  So the clean claim is:

  - Memory matters once the task becomes conversational.

  E0: Which condition is best?
  Concrete finding:

  - There is no universal winner.
  - In this confirmatory run, C is best overall by a very small margin over B.
  - D is not the winner here.

  So the correct paper claim is:

  - memory helps a lot
  - working memory does most of the lifting
  - episodic memory can help
  - full stack is not automatically best

  E0.5: How much memory is enough?
  From e05_confirm60_analysis.md:1:

  - Baseline A: 16.2%
  - B wm2: 77.1%
  - B wm5: 71.0%
  - C ep1: 72.4%
  - C ep3: 77.1%
  - D sem1: 72.7%
  - D sem2: 72.7%

  Concrete findings:

  1. Smaller working memory is better than larger working memory here.
      - wm2 beat wm5 by 6.1 points.
      - So carrying more recent turns did not help; it hurt.
  2. Selective episodic retrieval helps, but retrieval should stay small.
      - ep3 beat ep1 by 4.7 points in the confirmatory run.
      - Earlier exploratory run showed ep1 beat ep10.
      - So the stable finding is:
          - very large episodic retrieval is bad
          - small or moderate episodic retrieval is better
  3. Extra semantic hints are not helping.
      - sem1 and sem2 were identical at 72.7%
      - Earlier exploratory run also showed more semantic hints did not help
      - So semantic retrieval should stay narrow
  4. Best practical config right now
      - B wm2 is the strongest efficiency winner
      - C ep3 matches it on accuracy, but costs more memory
      - D is not currently justified

  What this means for your use case
  If your typical user asks 3 to 4 follow-up questions:

  - best default candidate: B wm2
  - best fallback if you need a little more recall: C ep3
  - not justified right now: heavier semantic memory

