• No LLM calls are needed for this. I implemented a pure analysis script at analyze_paper1_stats.py and ran it on the final reduced 120-session bundle. It uses Wilson
  95% confidence intervals, exact McNemar tests on matched turns, Holm correction, and paired bootstrap delta intervals.

  The output package is in e0_e05_final120_stats:

  - paper1_statistical_summary.md
  - overall_accuracy.csv
  - accuracy_by_tier.csv
  - accuracy_by_source.csv
  - accuracy_by_turn_band.csv
  - pairwise_significance.csv
  - stability_across_runs.csv
  - mse_ranking.csv

  What the stats now say:

  - A vs B wm2, C ep3, D sem1 are all decisively significant.
  - B wm2 vs C ep3 and B wm2 vs D sem1 are not significant at 0.05 after correction.
  - So the paper claim should be:
      - memory clearly helps
      - B wm2 is the best current operating point by accuracy and efficiency
      - but it is not statistically established as a universal winner over C ep3 or D sem1

  My answer on paper readiness: yes, this is now strong enough for an arXiv paper if you keep the claim disciplined. The evidence is interesting and useful:

  - large and stable memory benefit
  - Tier 1 control is clean
  - multi-turn effect is strong
  - “more memory is not always better” is supported
  - B wm2 is the practical default

